"Wiltshire K.H., Manly B.F.J.","The warming trend at Helgoland Roads, North Sea: Phytoplankton response",2004,"Helgoland Marine Research","58","4",,"269","273",,,10.1007/s10152-004-0196-0,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-11244305997&partnerID=40&md5=5083e665124ac1779d2b019c268e0f38","Biologische Anstalt Helgoland, A. Wegener Inst. Polar/Marine Res., P.O. Box 180, 27483 Helgoland, Germany; Western Ecosystems Technology, 217 South First Street, Laramie, WY 82070, United States","Wiltshire, K.H., Biologische Anstalt Helgoland, A. Wegener Inst. Polar/Marine Res., P.O. Box 180, 27483 Helgoland, Germany; Manly, B.F.J., Western Ecosystems Technology, 217 South First Street, Laramie, WY 82070, United States","We combine the temperature and phytoplankton data from one of the longest aquatic data sets in history, the Helgoland Roads (North Sea, 54°11.3'N, 7°54.0'E) timeseries to evaluate the effects of climate change on the base of marine food webs. The data shows that, despite an obvious warming of 1.1°C since 1962, the mean diatom day of the algal spring bloom is delayed and shifted to the end of the first quarter of the year. This is apparently related to a warming of the autumn (October-December) temperatures. It is the first indication of a warming related shift in phytoplankton succession, the consequences of which would range from lifecycle/food resource mismatches to regime shifts in the North Sea system. © Springer-Verlag and AWI 2004.","Diatoms; German Bight; Global warming; Spring bloom","algal bloom; climate change; global warming; phytoplankton; succession; Atlantic Ocean; Central Europe; Eastern Hemisphere; Eurasia; Europe; Frisian Islands; German Bight; Germany; Helgoland; North Frisian Islands; North Sea; oceanic regions; Schleswig-Holstein; World; algae; Bacillariophyta",,,,,,"Beare, D.J., Batten, S., Edwards, M., Reid, D.G., Prevalence of boreal Atlantic, temperate Atlantic and neritic zooplankton in the North Sea between 1958 and 1998 in 